<hl>
<seg id=1> China Will Carry On Open Financial Policy </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, January 16th(reporter: Xu Xingtang, Qian Yuhong). Dai Xianglong, the President of People's Bank of China, said that China will carry on with the open financial policy. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> At the press conference held toady for journalists from both at home and abroad, Dai Xianglong emphasized that China will not give up the open financial policy because of the financial turbulence in some of the Southeast Asian countries. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> He said that some foreign banks and insurance companies had set up branches in China, and business organizations set up by foreign investment had added up to more than 170 by the end of last year. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Henceforth, subsidiaries of foreign banks and insurance companies would be expanded to accomodate more RMB business transactions. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> At the same time, he emphasized that it would become more careful in the management of conditions affecting business launches in China, higher qualifications in ranking employees, and establishing the validity of its business. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He said that exchange under the RMB capital project had not been under any time restriction from the beginning, so there is no reason to prolong the process because of the financial crisis in Southeast Asia. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> But on the degree of openness of capital items, he stated that we should learn lessons from the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and take a more prudent attitude. </seg>
</p>
